I think it's worth generalising slightly (e.g., to cover `Î± := â„¤`). I'd also flip the two sides and add `simp`. So maybe something like:
```suggestion
@[to_additive, simp]
theorem prod_Ico_add_right_sub_eq [OrderedCancelAddCommMonoid Î±] [ExistsAddOfLE Î±] [LocallyFiniteOrder Î±]
    [Sub Î±] [OrderedSub Î±] (a b c : Î±) :
    âˆ x âˆˆ Ico (a + c) (b + c), f (x - c) = âˆ x âˆˆ Ico a b, f x := by
```

```suggestion
theorem prod_range_eq_mul_Ico (f : â„• â†’ M) {n : â„•} (hn : 0 < n) :
```

```suggestion
theorem iterate_apply_lie (D : LieDerivation R L L) (n : â„•) (a b : L) :
    D^[n] â…a, bâ† = âˆ‘ i in Finset.range (n + 1), Nat.choose n i â€¢ â…D^[i] a, D^[n - i] bâ† := by
```

On second thought, here's the statement I think we should prove:
```lean
open Finset Nat in
theorem iterate_apply_lie (D : LieDerivation R L L) (n : â„•) (a b : L) :
    D^[n] â…a, bâ† = âˆ‘ ij in antidiagonal n, choose n ij.1 â€¢ â…D^[ij.1] a, D^[ij.2] bâ† := by
  sorry
```
and if you really want the version using `Nat` subtraction then it should be the primed version `iterate_apply_lie'` and be a corollary (since I think the antidiagonal version will be easier to prove).
Brilliant! Yes, I much prefer using the antidiagonal (didnt know it had a name!), thanks for the suggestion!

It's so much better now! I decided to keep the previous version also, since it seems one has to explicitly provide the function inside the sum when calling `Nat.sum_antidiagonal_eq_sum_range_succ` which can be annoying.


```suggestion

```

